}
.EE
.SS JavaScript
The first part of the code defines the function
\f[CR]createImageObserver()\f[R] that we use to create
\f[CR]IntersectionObserver\f[R] objects and assign to the
\f[CR]imageObserver\f[R] variable.
We use a function because observer options can\(cqt be changed after
construction, and we want to be able to demonstrate the effects of
different \f[CR]scrollMargin\f[R] values.
.PP
The \f[CR]IntersectionObserver\f[R] is created with no
\f[CR]rootMargin\f[R], a near\-zero \f[CR]threshold\f[R], and a
\f[CR]scrollMargin\f[R] that takes its value from the \f[CR]margin\f[R]
input, and that will be applied to all sides of the scroll container.
.PP
The callback is called for all observed targets.
For intersecting targets it sets the \f[CR]img.src\f[R] to the name of
the image to be loaded (from the \f[CR]img.dataset.src\f[R]), logs the
intersection, and then stops observing the image.
.PP
The code at the end of the function calls
\f[CR]IntersectionObserver.observe()\f[R] on each image to start the
observer.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] rootContainer = document.getElementById(\(dqroot\-container\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] marginIndicator = document.getElementById(\(dqmargin\-indicator\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] carousel = document.querySelector(\(dq.carousel\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] lazyImages = carousel.querySelectorAll(\(dq.lazy\-carousel\-img\(dq);
\f[B]let\f[R] imageObserver;

\f[B]function\f[R] createImageObserver() {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (imageObserver) {
    imageObserver.disconnect();
  }

  \f[B]let\f[R] observerOptions = {
    root: rootContainer,
    rootMargin: \(dq0px\(dq, \f[I]// No extra margin\f[R]
    scrollMargin: \(ga${margin.valueAsNumber}px\(ga, \f[I]// No extra margin / Can be set\f[R]
    threshold: 0.01, \f[I]// Trigger when 1% of the image is visible\f[R]
  };

  imageObserver = \f[B]new\f[R] IntersectionObserver((entries, observer) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    entries.forEach((entry) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
      \f[B]if\f[R] (entry.isIntersecting) {
        \f[B]const\f[R] img = entry.target;
        log(\(gaintersect: ${img.dataset.src}\(ga); \f[I]// Only on first intersection\f[R]
        img.src = \(gahttps://mdn.github.io/shared\-assets/images/examples/${img.dataset.src}\(ga; \f[I]// Load image by setting src\f[R]
        img.classList.remove(\(dqlazy\-carousel\-img\(dq); \f[I]// Remove the class\f[R]
        observer.unobserve(img); \f[I]// Stop observing once loaded\f[R]
      }
    });
  }, observerOptions);

  \f[B]if\f[R] (margin.valueAsNumber < 0) {
    marginIndicator.style.width = \(ga${\-margin.valueAsNumber}px\(ga;
    marginIndicator.style.left = \(ga${margin.valueAsNumber}px\(ga;
    marginIndicator.style.backgroundColor = \(dqblue\(dq;
  } \f[B]else\f[R] {
    marginIndicator.style.width = \(ga${margin.valueAsNumber}px\(ga;
    marginIndicator.style.left = \(dq0px\(dq;
    marginIndicator.style.backgroundColor = \(dqgreen\(dq;
  }

  lazyImages.forEach((image) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    imageObserver.observe(image); \f[I]// Start observing each image\f[R]
  });
}
.EE
.PP
The following code creates the observer using
\f[CR]createImageObserver()\f[R] on start and whenever the
\f[CR]margin\f[R] input value is changed.
If the \f[CR]IntersectionObserver\f[R] interface isn\(cqt supported, it
loads all the images immediately.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\(dqIntersectionObserver\(dq \f[B]in\f[R] window) {
  createImageObserver();
  margin.addEventListener(\(dqinput\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    createImageObserver();
  });
} \f[B]else\f[R] {
  \f[I]// Fallback for browsers that don\(aqt support Intersection Observer\f[R]
  \f[I]// Loads all images immediately if Intersection Observer is not supported.\f[R]
  lazyImages.forEach((img) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    img.src = img.dataset.src;
    img.classList.remove(\(dqlazy\-carousel\-img\(dq);
  });
  console.warn(
    \(dqIntersection Observer not supported. All carousel images loaded.\(dq,
  );
}
.EE
.SS Results
Scroll down to display the carousel.
The visible images should immediately load.
If you scroll the carousel right, you should observe that the images are
loaded as soon as the element becomes visible.
.PP
You can use the provided control to change the scroll margin percentage
(after resetting the example) If you set a positive value like 20px the
clip rectangle of the scroll container will be increased by 20px, and
you should observe that images are detected and loaded before they come
into view.
Similarly, a negative value will mean that the intersection is detected
once images are already in view.
